{{Main|Maryland Terrapins football under Jim Tatum (1947â1955)}} {{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=1952 |Team=Maryland Terrapins |Image= |Conference=Southern Conference |Division= |ShortConference=SoCon |Record= 7â2 |ConfRecord= N/A<ref name=note group=nb>Maryland was a member of the Southern Conference, but was disallowed from playing any conference opponents during the 1952 season as part of the sanctions for violating the ban on postseason play the year prior.</ref> |CoachRank= |APRank= 13 |HeadCoach=[[Jim Tatum]] |OffCoach= |DefCoach= |OScheme=[[Split-T]] |DScheme= |StadiumArena= |Champion= |BowlTourney= |BowlTourneyResult= }} The '''1952 Maryland Terrapins football team''' represented the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[college football]] in its [[1952 college football season|32nd season]] as a member of the [[Southern Conference]]. However, during the 1952 season, Maryland underwent sanctions by the Southern Conference that disallowed the team from playing any conference opponents. This was in response to Maryland's violation of a newly instituted ban on postseason play the year prior by its participation in the [[1952 Sugar Bowl]].<ref name=acc>K. Adam Powell and Woody Durham, ''Border Wars: The First Fifty Years of Atlantic Coast Conference Football'', p. xvi, Scarecrow Press, ISBN 0-8108-4839-2, 2004.</ref> [[Jim Tatum]] served as the head coach for the sixth season of his [[Maryland Terrapins football under Jim Tatum (1947â1955)|nine-year tenure]]. The team compiled a 7â2 record The loss against 14th-ranked {{cfb link|year=1952|team=Ole Miss Rebels|title=Mississippi}} ended Maryland's school-record 22-game winning streak.<ref name="umd">[http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/md/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/08guide-11.pdf Year-by-Year Results] (PDF), ''2008 Maryland Football Media Guide'', University of Maryland, 2008. Accessed 2009-06-15. [http://www.webcitation.org/query?id=1245281443511493 Archived] 2009-06-17.</ref> After the season, Maryland left the Southern Conference in order to become a founding member of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC).<ref name=acc/>
